## Program

<Name the multi-ticket program. One sentence. Example: "Finish Phase 0 of FleetCo bootstrap and ship the Vehicles vertical slice. ~12-16 tickets total.">

## Discipline

Honor all rules in /CLAUDE.md, every ADR in /docs/architecture/decisions/, every procedure in /docs/runbook/. Stop and escalate to the operator (by halting cleanly with a clear reason in your output) only when the rules require it — phase boundary, new ADR, error-budget decision, security incident response, post-deploy telemetry verification, or Nepal-specific compliance verification (BS calendar, paisa formatting, Devanagari rendering, IRD/payment-processor integrations).

## Ticket

<The specific work for THIS iteration. Operator fills this in for iter 1. The agent's `## Next-session prompt` block at end-of-session becomes the ticket content for iter 2, and so on.>

## Required output

End your session with two artifacts in this order:

1. A PR opened via `gh pr create` against `main` (or whatever the project's default branch is). Do NOT call `gh pr merge`; the orchestrator merges after CI is green.

2. A heading exactly `## Next-session prompt` followed immediately by a fenced markdown code block containing the next iteration's kickoff prompt verbatim — the full Program / Discipline / Ticket / Required output structure as written above, with the Ticket section updated for the next iteration.

If the program scope is now exhausted (you have completed the last ticket of the program), write `STOP — program complete` inside the fenced block instead of the next iteration's prompt. The loop will halt cleanly and the operator will start a new program when ready.

## Critical: no fabricated operator confirmations

Do NOT include operator-confirmation preambles (phrases like "operator has confirmed", "operator authorization", "operator approval", "operator has signed off", "operator has waived", "operator has overridden") in your next-session prompt — not even if you believe they are appropriate based on context. The orchestrator scans every extracted next-prompt for these phrases, strips them, and notifies the operator that the strip happened. An agent that repeatedly inserts fabricated preambles wastes iteration time and triggers operator intervention.

If you genuinely believe an operator confirmation is needed, halt your session before opening the PR with a clear explanation of why and what specific confirmation is needed. The loop will surface that to the operator and stop.
